SUMMARY:🏫 Class: CE/EE 442/426-L1
UID:26a2d8e1-1b06-493d-a5f7-3a7def8edfb7@26a2.org
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260203
DESCRIPTION:Link: https://hulms.instructure.com/courses/4981/discussion_topics/62217\n\nDear Class\,\nHere’s a quick recap of what we covered in Lecture #4 and what you need to do for the upcoming assignment.\nKey topics from yesterday\n1) Agentic AI: why it changes the risk picture\n\nWe discussed how agentic AI increases the attack surface compared to “classic” GenAI/chatbots because agents can take actions via tools (e.g.\, accessing files/drive\, sending emails/SMS\, making outbound calls\, running workflows\, etc.).\nThis means failures can move from “bad text output” to real-world actions taken on a user’s/organization’s behalf.\n\n2) Safety vs. Security (and how to tell the difference)\n\nSafety = preventing unintentional harm (intent/behavior control).\n\nExamples in agentic AI: misaligned goals\, runaway actions\, unintended harmful outcomes.\nControls: alignment\, guardrails\, constraints\, stop conditions\, human-in-the-loop.\n\nSecurity = defending against deliberate threats (access/abuse control).\n\nExamples in agentic AI: prompt injection\, account/tool hijacking\, data exfiltration\, abuse of permissions.\nControls: authentication/authorization\, sandboxing\, secrets isolation\, least privilege tools.\n\nWe also highlighted that bias is primarily a safety concern (intrinsic to the system’s behavior)\, even though safety/security can sometimes overlap.\n\n3) Industry frameworks you should know (and use as checklists)\nWe reviewed three key references you’ll use to reason about and test systems:\n\nOWASP Top 10 (Web App Security) — common web application risks like injection\, misconfigurations\, broken access control\, etc.\nOWASP Top 10 (LLM Applications) — LLM-specific risks like prompt injection\, sensitive info disclosure\, excessive agency\, training data poisoning\, etc.\nMITRE ATLAS / ATLAS Matrix — a threat matrix/framework for AI/ML systems covering attacker behaviors (recon → access → execution → exfiltration → impact).\n\nWe also walked through examples like:\n\nTraining data poisoning (poisoned training or fine-tuning data impacting model behavior).\nA multi-turn jailbreak (“crescendo”) example to illustrate how prompt injection can gradually steer a model toward disallowed outputs.\n\n4) Hyperscalers &amp\; Responsible AI tooling (Azure / AWS / GCP)\nWe talked through how major cloud platforms provide built-in capabilities for:\n\ncontent safety filters\, prompt defense\, evaluations\, explainability\, monitoring\, and transparency\nred teaming (authorized “attack simulation” to test defenses)\n\nWe also mentioned major standards:\n\nNIST AI RMF\, ISO 42001\, and EU AI Act (noting the EU AI Act is enforceable law\, unlike most guidance/frameworks).\n\n&nbsp\;\nThe details for this week's assignment are available here: A3: LLM Security Helper App.\nLecture slides have been added to the week 4 module and the supplemental material for this week is available here: Readings &amp\; Supplemental Material.\nIf you have questions\, reach out to the course RAs&nbsp\;or message the instructor.\n&nbsp\;\nBest\,CS 435 Team
SUMMARY:📢 Lecture 4 Recap (GenAI Security & Safety) + Assignment Demo Next Class (CS 435-L1)
UID:6fa4d8f2-52f1-4ccb-9319-4df8b3eb7f87@6fa4.org
END:VEVENT
