BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260208
DESCRIPTION:Link: https://hulms.instructure.com/courses/4981/discussion_topics/62376\n\nDear Class\,\nWe want to share an important update regarding class participation and attendance expectations for this course.\nOver the past few sessions\, inconsistent attendance and limited responsiveness during live classes has been observed. This course is designed to be highly interactive\, discussion-driven\, and participatory. Active engagement is not optional—it is a core part of the learning experience and essential to achieving the course outcomes.\nEffective immediately\, camera-on participation during live class sessions will be required.Students who attend with cameras off will be marked absent\, except in cases of documented or pre-approved exceptions.\nThis policy is being introduced to:\n* Ensure meaningful engagement and accountability* Support interactive discussions\, cold-calling\, and real-time feedback* Maintain fairness and consistency across the class\nI recognize that genuine constraints can arise. If you have a legitimate reason (technical\, medical\, or personal) that prevents camera-on participation\, please discuss it with me directly in advance\, and we will handle it reasonably on a case-by-case basis.\nWhile this expectation would ideally have been stated in the syllabus upfront\, it is still well within instructional norms\, and it aligns with the collaborative\, discussion-oriented nature of this course.\nI appreciate your cooperation and professionalism as we move forward. My goal is to ensure a high-quality learning environment where everyone benefits fully from the experience.\nBest regards\,CS435 RAs\nOn behalf of Dr. Adnan Masood
SUMMARY:📢 Class Participation Policy Update – Camera-On Requirement (CS 435-L1)
UID:18a2c4d1-7d3a-4bda-a5ad-96399d9d231c@18a2.org
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260121
DESCRIPTION:Link: https://hulms.instructure.com/courses/4981/discussion_topics/61780\n\nDear class\nQuick recap:\n1. Five Tribes of ML and why Generative AI ≠ predictive modeling for tasks like ranking and forecasting - &nbsp\;The concept of moat / USP in AI products (why “just an API + prompt” isn’t enough) - High-level LLM application stack (data pipelines\, vector DBs\, caching\, hosting)\n2. Dr. Abdella' Guest lecture on Transformers: tokenization\, embeddings\, attention\, masking\, and encoder–decoder architecture&nbsp\;\nQuiz update: The next class quiz will be based on BOTH my lecture and the guest lecture. Please re-watch the full lecture recording and review the Transformer concepts carefully.\nAssignment 1 — Token Counter Tool:\nBuild a tool that takes input text + a selected LLM model (any 3 models) and outputs the token count.CLI/terminal-based is fine (UI optional).Submit as a PUBLIC GitHub repository with a clear README.Due: Sunday night 1/25 - 11:59pm (before next class).\nThanks\,Adnan
SUMMARY:📢 Lecture Recap\, Quiz Update\, and Assignment 1 (CS 435-L1)
UID:c0b7f82f-db0b-4d89-8ead-1e551365dffa@c0b7.org
END:VEVENT
